{"title_page": "SuperBrawl Revenge", "text_new": "{{short description|2001 World Championship Wrestling pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = SuperBrawl Revenge\n|image      = SuperBrawl_Revenge.jpg\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]], [[Bill Goldberg|Goldberg]], [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]], [[Scott Steiner]], and [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]].\n|tagline    = A Path Of Destruction...A Night Of Vengeance.\n|promotion  = [[World Championship Wrestling]]\n|date       = February 18, 2001\n|venue      = [[Nashville Municipal Auditorium]]\n|city       = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n|attendance = 4,395<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/wcw/wcwsuper.htm | title=WCW SuperBrawl | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603015414/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/wcw/wcwsuper.htm | archivedate=2008-06-03 }}</ref>\n|lastevent  = [[WCW Sin|Sin]]\n|nextevent  = [[WCW Greed|Greed]]\n|event      =[[SuperBrawl]]\n|lastevent2 =[[SuperBrawl 2000|2000]]\n|nextevent2 =''Final''\n}}\n'''SuperBrawl Revenge''' was the eleventh and final [[SuperBrawl]] [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of NWA/WCW closed-circuit events and pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW). It took place on February 18, 2001 from the [[Nashville Municipal Auditorium]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].\n\nThis was the last SuperBrawl event and the penultimate WCW pay-per-view before the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation/now Entertainment]] (WWF/now WWE) purchased WCW in March 2001. Along with [[SuperBrawl IV]], it was one of only two SuperBrawls never released on home video.\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|two out of three]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls count anywhere match|falls count anywhere]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|loser leaves town match]] between [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Kevin Nash]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]. Steiner retained the title, forcing Nash to retire from WCW.<ref name=\"411mania\">{{cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/the-furious-flashbacks-wcw-superbrawl-revenge/|title=The Furious Flashbacks \u2013 WCW Superbrawl Revenge|date=October 18, 2007|accessdate=2017-02-23|publisher=411Mania}}</ref> Featured matches on the [[Card (sports)#Undercard|undercard]] were [[Diamond Dallas Page]] versus [[Jeff Jarrett]], [[Ernest Miller]] versus [[Lance Storm]] for the position of [[Professional wrestling authority figures#Commissioner|WCW Commissioner]], title defenses of the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship|World Tag Team]], [[WWE United States Championship|United States Heavyweight]] and [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|Cruiserweight]] [[Professional wrestling championship|Championship]]s and matches to determine the #1 contenders for the Cruiserweight and the World Tag Team titles.<ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/superbrawl.htm|title=SuperBrawl PPV Results|accessdate=2017-02-23|publisher=The History of WWE}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\nThe [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] at Superbrawl Revenge involved professional wrestlers performing as [[Character (arts)|characters]] in [[Kayfabe|scripted events]] pre-determined<ref name=\"HSW\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm|title=How Pro Wrestling Works|last=Grabianowski|first=Ed|work=HowStuffWorks, Inc.|publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> by the hosting [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]], WCW. [[narrative thread|Storylines]] between the characters played out on WCW's television programs, ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]'', ''[[WCW Thunder|Thunder]]'' and ''[[WCW Worldwide|WorldWide]]''.\n\nThe main rivalry heading into the event was between [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Kevin Nash]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]. Steiner retained the title against [[Road Warrior Animal]], [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]] and [[Jeff Jarrett]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|four corners match]] at [[WCW Sin|Sin]]. The following night, on ''Nitro'', Steiner cut a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|promo]] on injuring Vicious' leg and forcing [[Bill Goldberg|Goldberg]] out of WCW. His boasting led to [[Professional wrestling authority figures#Commissioner|Commissioner]] [[Ernest Miller]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|booking]] a match between Steiner and [[Kevin Nash]] later in the night, which ended in a disqualification after the [[Magnificent Seven (professional wrestling)|Magnificent Seven]] attacked Nash. On the January 17 episode of ''Thunder'', the Magnificent Seven interfered in a match between Jarrett and [[Diamond Dallas Page]], prompting Nash, Miller and [[KroniK]] to come to the rescue. On the special ''Tuesday Nitro'' edition of ''Nitro'' on January 23, a match was made between Nash and [[Buff Bagwell]] to determine Steiner's opponent for the title at SuperBrawl Revenge. On that same night, [[Lex Luger]] defeated Diamond Dallas Page to become the [[Professional wrestling match types#Special referee|special guest referee]] for the main event match between Bagwell and Nash. Nash defeated Bagwell to become the #1 contender for the title. On the February 5 episode of ''Monday Nitro'', Nash and [[Rick Steiner]] took on Scott Steiner in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]], where Rick turned on Nash, allowing Scott to pick up the win and join the Magnificent Seven. On the February 7 episode of ''Thunder'', [[The Insiders (professional wrestling)|The Insiders]] (Kevin Nash and Diamond Dallas Page) defeated Jeff Jarrett and Rick Steiner.\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ Other on-screen personnel\n!Role:\n!Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=3|Commentator\n|Scott Hudson\n|-\n|[[Tony Schiavone]]\n|-\n|[[Mike Tenay]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Interviewer\n|[[Gene Okerlund]]\n|-\n|Mike Tenay\n|-\n|rowspan=4|Referee\n|[[Mark \"Slick\" Johnson|Mark Johnson]]\n|-\n|[[Nick Hamilton|Nick Patrick]]\n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (wrestling referee)|Charles Robinson]]\n|-\n|[[Billy Silverman]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Ring announcer\n|[[Michael Buffer]]\n|-\n|[[David Penzer]]\n|}\n\n===Pre-Show===\nBefore the event aired live on pay-per-view, [[Chris Harris (wrestler)|Chris Harris]] defeated [[Kid Romeo]] in a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|non-televised match]].<ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n===Preliminary matches===\nThe first match at the event was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|six-man elimination match]] to determine the #1 contender for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WCW Cruiserweight Championship]] for the following month's pay-per-view [[WCW Greed|Greed]]. The match was originally scheduled to be between [[Billy Kidman]], [[Shannon Moore]], [[Kaz Hayashi]], [[Jimmy Wang Yang|Yun Yang]], [[Jamie Noble|Jamie Knoble]] and [[Evan Karagias]]. However, Kidman was attacked by [[Road Warrior Animal]] before the match and was replaced by [[Gregory Helms|Shane Helms]]. Karagias was the first to be eliminated when Yang [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] him after a [[neckbreaker]]. Shortly after, Knoble eliminated Yang with a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Reverse piledriver)|jumping reverse piledriver]]. Moore then eliminated Knoble with a ''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving leg drop bulldog|Bottoms Up]]''. Helms followed it up by eliminating Moore with a ''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Spinning headlock elbow drop|Nightmare on Helms Street]]'' and then pinned Hayashi after a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Vertebreaker|Vertebreaker]] to win the match and earn the title shot for Greed.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nThe next match was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Singles matches|singles match]] between [[Bill DeMott|Hugh Morrus]] and [[Jerry Tuite|The Wall]], stemming from Wall's betrayal of Morrus, resulting in the breakup of [[Misfits in Action]]. Both men traded moves until Morrus delivered a [[Suplex#German suplex|German suplex]] and a ''[[Moonsault|No Laughing Matter]]'' to win the match. Morrus delivered the move again after the match.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nThe third match was a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]] for the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]. [[Chuck Palumbo]] and [[Sean O'Haire]] defended the titles against [[Mark Jindrak]] and [[Shawn Stasiak]]. Both teams were former members of the [[Natural Born Thrillers]]. After a back and forth action, Palumbo and O'Haire finished Stasiak when Palumbo delivered a ''[[Superkick|Jungle Kick]]'' and O\u2019Haire delivered a ''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#High-angle senton bomb|Seanton Bomb]]'' to win the match and retain the titles.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n[[Chavo Guerrero|Chavo Guerrero, Jr.]] defended the Cruiserweight Championship against [[Rey Mysterio|Rey Misterio, Jr.]] in the fourth match. Mysterio started the action with high paced quick and high-flying action. Both men traded moves until Guerrero brought a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Foreign object|steel chair]] into the ring and placed it in the corner. He tried to toss Mysterio into the cornered chair but Mysterio avoided the move and gained the momentum. Mysterio tried to close the match by hitting Guerrero with the chair following a [[DDT (professional wrestling)#Tornado DDT|Tornado DDT]] but the [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]] took it away. Guerrero took advantage of the referee's distraction and grabbed another chair, hitting Mysterio with it and delivering a [[Brainbuster]] to win the match and retain his title.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nIn the next match, [[Rick Steiner]] defended the [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Goldust|Dustin Rhodes]]. Steiner won the match by exposing a turnbuckle and slamming Rhodes face-first into the exposed turnbuckle and pinning him by putting his feet on ropes to gain leverage. As a result, Steiner retained his title. After the match, Steiner delivered a ''[[Professional wrestling throws#Death Valley|Steiner Driver]]'' and cut a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|promo]] before going for another post-match assault on Rhodes but Rhodes countered with a ''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Low blow|Shattered Dreams]]''.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nTotally Buffed ([[Lex Luger]] and [[Buff Bagwell]]) were scheduled to take on [[KroniK]] ([[Brian Adams (wrestler)|Brian Adams]] and [[Bryan Clark]]) in a tag team match to determine the #1 contenders for the World Tag Team Championship at Greed. However, Clark was injured before the match but appeared alongside Adams but Bagwell hit him with a steel chair to take him out of the match. Adams was left alone to fend off Totally Buffed, making it a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]]. Adams tried to control the early portion of the match but was dominated by his opponents due to number disadvantage. Adams made a comeback by [[powerslam]]ming Luger until [[Mike Awesome]] showed up and was disguised as Clark. He attacked Adams until Clark came to the ringside to brawl with Awesome in the aisle. Luger applied a ''[[Backbreaker#Argentine backbreaker rack|Torture Rack]]'' on Adams and Bagwell delivered a ''[[Neckbreaker#Flying neckbreaker|Buff Blockbuster]]'' to Adams to win the match and earn the title shot for the tag team titles.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n[[Lance Storm]] put his newly won position of [[Professional wrestling authority figures#Commissioner|WCW Commissioner]] against [[Ernest Miller]]. Miller started the match with his signature kicks until Storm began targeting his leg to slow the momentum. Miller attempted at a ''[[540 kick|Feliner]]'' but Storm countered with a [[Takedown (grappling)|single leg takedown]] and applied a ''[[Boston crab#Single leg Boston crab|Maple Leaf]]'' which Miller reversed and delivered an [[Professional wrestling attacks#Enzuigiri|enzuigiri]]. [[Mike Sanders (wrestler)|Mike Sanders]] appeared ringside to distract Miller, but Miller's [[Manager (professional wrestling)|valet]] [[The Nitro Girls|Miss Jones]] kicked him. Miller took advantage of the situation and hit a ''Feliner'' for the win and won the position of WCW Commissioner, which would be effective by mid-night. After the match, Miller was ejected by the arena as the position had not been effective yet.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nThe final match on the undercard was [[Diamond Dallas Page]] versus [[Jeff Jarrett]]. However, Jarrett goaded Page into fighting [[Chris Kanyon]] into a match after a brawl between Page and Kanyon on that week's ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Nitro]]''. Kanyon launched a sneak attack on Page from behind but Page soon countered Kanyon's offensive. Both men exchanged moves until Kanyon tried to win by delivering a ''[[Cutter (professional wrestling)|Kanyon Kutter]]'' but got a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Near-fall|near-fall]]. Kanyon called Jarrett to hit Page with an ''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Guitar shot|Acoustic Equalizer]]'' but Jarrett missed it and Page took advantage with a [[Pin (professional wrestling)#Roll-up|roll-up]] but Kanyon kicked out at 2. The referee was knocked out and Jarrett entered the ring to hit Page with a ''[[Facebuster#Forward Russian legsweep|Stroke]]''. Kanyon followed it with a ''[[Facebuster#Reverse STO|Flatliner]]'' to win the match. After the match, Jarrett and Page began their match. Jarrett took advantage of Page's condition but Page managed to counter with a brawl at ringside. Page tried his ''[[Cutter (professional wrestling)|Diamond Cutter]]'' on Jarrett on the announce table but Jarrett shoved him into [[Tony Schiavone]]. Jarrett controlled the match until Page made a comeback near the closing moments of the match. Kanyon returned to the ring to pull Page out of the ring, allowing Jarrett to nail Page with a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Chair shot|chair shot]] and got a near-fall. Jarrett went for his ''Acoustic Equalizer'' on Page but he ducked and Kanyon was hit with it, allowing Page to deliver a ''Diamond Cutter'' to Jarrett to get the win.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n===Main event match===\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|loser leaves WCW match]] between [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Kevin Nash]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]. Nash won the title in just [[Squash (professional wrestling)|seventeen seconds]] by pinning Steiner after hitting him with a title belt. After the match, [[Ric Flair]] announced that the match was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|two out of three falls match]] contested under [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|no disqualification rules]], thus continuing the match. Diamond Dallas Page appeared at the ringside to help Nash in the situation but Totally Buffed came to the ringside to take him out of the equation. Steiner's bodyguard [[Melinda O'Hearn|Midajah]] interfered in the match and Steiner hit Nash with a steel pipe outside the ring. Steiner was unable to pick Nash and toss him into the ring, so Flair made it a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls count anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] and Steiner pinned Nash to win the second fall and even the score. The two men continued the action in the third fall. Flair handed a steel chair to Steiner and he hit Nash with it while Midajah held him. Steiner applied a ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Camel clutch|Steiner Recliner]]'' on Nash but Nash escaped it. He tossed Steiner into the corner with a [[Professional wrestling throws#Snake Eyes|Snake Eyes]] and a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big boot|big boot]], followed by a ''[[Powerbomb#Release powerbomb|Jackknife Powerbomb]]''. Nash attempted a pinfall but the pinfall was broken up by Midajah. Nash delivered a [[Powerslam#Side slam|side slam]] to Midajah. Flair tossed another chair to Steiner, allowing Steiner to hit Nash with the chair and he applied a ''Steiner Recliner'' to knock out Nash to get the win and retain the title, thus forcing Nash to leave WCW.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[Shane Helms]] got his title shot at the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WCW Cruiserweight Championship]] at [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.]] at the [[WCW Greed|Greed]] pay-per-view, where he defeated Guerrero to win the title. Totally Buffed received their title shot at the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]] against [[Chuck Palumbo]] and [[Sean O'Haire]] at the event but failed to win the title. [[Diamond Dallas Page]] got a title shot for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Scott Steiner]] due to interfering in Steiner's title match against Nash at SuperBrawl Revenge. Steiner defeated Page to retain the title in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls count anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] at Greed, but lost the title to [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (who held the United States Championship) in a winner-take-all match on the final episode of ''WCW Monday Nitro'' on March 26, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/miscppv.html#greed|title=WCW Greed results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref name=play>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/06/22/1098665.html|title=Booker T to play two more years|author=Jason Clevett|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=April 17, 2008|date=June 22, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n|dark1=yes\n|match1=[[Chris Harris (wrestler)|Chris Harris]] defeated [[Kid Romeo]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=N/A\n|match2=[[Gregory Helms|Shane Helms]] defeated [[Evan Karagias]], [[Kaz Hayashi]], [[Jamie Noble|Jamie Knoble]], [[Shannon Moore]] and [[Jimmy Yang|Yun Yang]]\n|stip2=6 man [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|Elimination match]]\n|time2=17:30\n|match3=[[Bill DeMott|Hugh Morrus]] defeated [[Jerry Tuite|The Wall]]\n|stip3=Singles match\n|time3=09:43\n|match4=[[Sean O'Haire]] and [[Chuck Palumbo]] (c) defeated [[Mark Jindrak]] and [[Shawn Stasiak]]\n|stip4=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types|Tag team match]] for the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]\n|time4=11:37\n|match5=[[Chavo Guerrero Jr.]] (c) defeated [[Rey Mysterio|Rey Misterio Jr.]]\n|stip5=Singles match for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WCW Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time5=15:54\n|match6=[[Rick Steiner]] (c) defeated [[Goldust|Dustin Rhodes]]\n|stip6=Singles match for the [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time6=09:11\n|match7=Totally Buffed ([[Lex Luger]] and [[Buff Bagwell]]) defeated [[Brian Adams (wrestler)|Brian Adams]]\n|stip7=[[professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|Handicap match]]\n|time7=06:25\n|match8=[[Ernest Miller]] (with [[The Nitro Girls|Ms. Jones]]) defeated [[Lance Storm]]\n|stip8=Singles match for the position of WCW Commissioner\n|time8=08:07\n|match9=[[Chris Kanyon]] defeated [[Diamond Dallas Page]]\n|stip9=Singles match\n|time9=08:15\n|match10=Diamond Dallas Page defeated [[Jeff Jarrett]]\n|stip10=Singles match\n|time10=08:30\n|match11=[[Scott Steiner]] (c) (with [[Midajah]] and [[Ric Flair]]) defeated [[Kevin Nash]] 2\u20131\n|stip11=[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Two-out-of-three falls]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|\"loser leaves WCW\" match]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time11=11:04\n}}\n\n===No. 1 Contender's match eliminations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Elimination no.\n!Wrestler\n!Eliminated by\n!Elimination move\n!Time\n|-\n|1\n|Evan Karagias\n|Yun Yang\n|[[Neckbreaker]]\n|10:21\n|-\n|2\n|Yun Yang\n|Jamie Knoble\n|[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Reverse piledriver)|Jumping reverse piledriver]]\n|10:51\n|-\n|3\n|Jamie Knoble\n|Shannon Moore\n|''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving leg drop bulldog|Bottoms Up]]''\n|11:58\n|-\n|4\n|Shannon Moore\n|Shane Helms\n|''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Spinning headlock elbow drop|Nightmare on Helms Street]]''\n|15:11\n|-\n|5\n|Kaz Hayashi\n|Shane Helms\n|[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Vertebreaker|Vertebreaker]]\n|17:30\n|-\n!Winner:Billy Kidman\n|colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"#f2f2f2\"|Billy Kidman\n|}\n\n===Two out of three falls match results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Fall no.\n!Fall scoring move\n!Time\n|-\n|1\n|Nash pinned Steiner after hitting him with the [[Professional wrestling championship|title belt]]\n|00:17\n|-\n|2\n|Steiner pinned Nash after hitting him with a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Foreign object|steel pipe]]\n|02:47\n|-\n|3\n|Steiner hit Nash with a steel chair and won via knockout with a ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Camel clutch|Steiner Recliner]]''\n|11:04\n|-\n!Winner:\n|colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"#f2f2f2\"|Scott Steiner\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2001 WCW pay-per-view events}}\n{{WCWPPV|SuperBrawl}}\n\n[[Category:SuperBrawl|SuperBrawl 11]]\n[[Category:Events in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:2001 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:February 2001 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2001 World Championship Wrestling pay-per-view events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 World Championship Wrestling pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = SuperBrawl Revenge\n|image      = SuperBrawl_Revenge.jpg\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]], [[Bill Goldberg|Goldberg]], [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]], [[Scott Steiner]], and [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]].\n|tagline    = A Path Of Destruction...A Night Of Vengeance.\n|promotion  = [[World Championship Wrestling]]\n|date       = February 18, 2001\n|venue      = [[Nashville Municipal Auditorium]]\n|city       = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n|attendance = 4,395<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/wcw/wcwsuper.htm | title=WCW SuperBrawl | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603015414/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/wcw/wcwsuper.htm | archivedate=2008-06-03 }}</ref>\n|lastevent  = [[WCW Sin|Sin]]\n|nextevent  = [[WCW Greed|Greed]]\n|event      =[[SuperBrawl]]\n|lastevent2 =[[SuperBrawl 2000|2000]]\n|nextevent2 =''Final''}}\n\n'''SuperBrawl Revenge''' was the eleventh and final [[SuperBrawl]] [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of NWA/WCW closed-circuit events and pay-per-view events|event]] produced by [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW). It took place on February 18, 2001 from the [[Nashville Municipal Auditorium]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].\n\nThis was the last SuperBrawl event and the penultimate WCW pay-per-view before the [[World Wrestling Entertainment|World Wrestling Federation/now Entertainment]] (WWF/now WWE) purchased WCW in March 2001. Along with [[SuperBrawl IV]], it was one of only two SuperBrawls never released on home video.\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|two out of three]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls count anywhere match|falls count anywhere]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|loser leaves town match]] between [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Kevin Nash]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]. Steiner retained the title, forcing Nash to retire from WCW.<ref name=\"411mania\">{{cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/the-furious-flashbacks-wcw-superbrawl-revenge/|title=The Furious Flashbacks \u2013 WCW Superbrawl Revenge|date=October 18, 2007|accessdate=2017-02-23|publisher=411Mania}}</ref> Featured matches on the [[Card (sports)#Undercard|undercard]] were [[Diamond Dallas Page]] versus [[Jeff Jarrett]], [[Ernest Miller]] versus [[Lance Storm]] for the position of [[Professional wrestling authority figures#Commissioner|WCW Commissioner]], title defenses of the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship|World Tag Team]], [[WWE United States Championship|United States Heavyweight]] and [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|Cruiserweight]] [[Professional wrestling championship|Championship]]s and matches to determine the #1 contenders for the Cruiserweight and the World Tag Team titles.<ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/superbrawl.htm|title=SuperBrawl PPV Results|accessdate=2017-02-23|publisher=The History of WWE}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\nThe [[Professional wrestling match types|professional wrestling matches]] at Superbrawl Revenge involved professional wrestlers performing as [[Character (arts)|characters]] in [[Kayfabe|scripted events]] pre-determined<ref name=\"HSW\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/pro-wrestling.htm|title=How Pro Wrestling Works|last=Grabianowski|first=Ed|work=HowStuffWorks, Inc.|publisher=[[Discovery Communications]]|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> by the hosting [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]], WCW. [[narrative thread|Storylines]] between the characters played out on WCW's television programs, ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]'', ''[[WCW Thunder|Thunder]]'' and ''[[WCW Worldwide|WorldWide]]''.\n\nThe main rivalry heading into the event was between [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Kevin Nash]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]. Steiner retained the title against [[Road Warrior Animal]], [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]] and [[Jeff Jarrett]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic non-elimination matches|four corners match]] at [[WCW Sin|Sin]]. The following night, on ''Nitro'', Steiner cut a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|promo]] on injuring Vicious' leg and forcing [[Bill Goldberg|Goldberg]] out of WCW. His boasting led to [[Professional wrestling authority figures#Commissioner|Commissioner]] [[Ernest Miller]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|booking]] a match between Steiner and [[Kevin Nash]] later in the night, which ended in a disqualification after the [[Magnificent Seven (professional wrestling)|Magnificent Seven]] attacked Nash. On the January 17 episode of ''Thunder'', the Magnificent Seven interfered in a match between Jarrett and [[Diamond Dallas Page]], prompting Nash, Miller and [[KroniK]] to come to the rescue. On the special ''Tuesday Nitro'' edition of ''Nitro'' on January 23, a match was made between Nash and [[Buff Bagwell]] to determine Steiner's opponent for the title at SuperBrawl Revenge. On that same night, [[Lex Luger]] defeated Diamond Dallas Page to become the [[Professional wrestling match types#Special referee|special guest referee]] for the main event match between Bagwell and Nash. Nash defeated Bagwell to become the #1 contender for the title. On the February 5 episode of ''Monday Nitro'', Nash and [[Rick Steiner]] took on Scott Steiner in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]], where Rick turned on Nash, allowing Scott to pick up the win and join the Magnificent Seven. On the February 7 episode of ''Thunder'', [[The Insiders (professional wrestling)|The Insiders]] (Kevin Nash and Diamond Dallas Page) defeated Jeff Jarrett and Rick Steiner.\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ Other on-screen personnel\n!Role:\n!Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=3|Commentator\n|Scott Hudson\n|-\n|[[Tony Schiavone]]\n|-\n|[[Mike Tenay]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Interviewer\n|[[Gene Okerlund]]\n|-\n|Mike Tenay\n|-\n|rowspan=4|Referee\n|[[Mark \"Slick\" Johnson|Mark Johnson]]\n|-\n|[[Nick Hamilton|Nick Patrick]]\n|-\n|[[Charles Robinson (wrestling referee)|Charles Robinson]]\n|-\n|[[Billy Silverman]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Ring announcer\n|[[Michael Buffer]]\n|-\n|[[David Penzer]]\n|}\n\n===Pre-Show===\nBefore the event aired live on pay-per-view, [[Chris Harris (wrestler)|Chris Harris]] defeated [[Kid Romeo]] in a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Dark match|non-televised match]].<ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n===Preliminary matches===\nThe first match at the event was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|six-man elimination match]] to determine the #1 contender for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WCW Cruiserweight Championship]] for the following month's pay-per-view [[WCW Greed|Greed]]. The match was originally scheduled to be between [[Billy Kidman]], [[Shannon Moore]], [[Kaz Hayashi]], [[Jimmy Wang Yang|Yun Yang]], [[Jamie Noble|Jamie Knoble]] and [[Evan Karagias]]. However, Kidman was attacked by [[Road Warrior Animal]] before the match and was replaced by [[Gregory Helms|Shane Helms]]. Karagias was the first to be eliminated when Yang [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pinned]] him after a [[neckbreaker]]. Shortly after, Knoble eliminated Yang with a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Reverse piledriver)|jumping reverse piledriver]]. Moore then eliminated Knoble with a ''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving leg drop bulldog|Bottoms Up]]''. Helms followed it up by eliminating Moore with a ''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Spinning headlock elbow drop|Nightmare on Helms Street]]'' and then pinned Hayashi after a [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Vertebreaker|Vertebreaker]] to win the match and earn the title shot for Greed.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nThe next match was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Singles matches|singles match]] between [[Bill DeMott|Hugh Morrus]] and [[Jerry Tuite|The Wall]], stemming from Wall's betrayal of Morrus, resulting in the breakup of [[Misfits in Action]]. Both men traded moves until Morrus delivered a [[Suplex#German suplex|German suplex]] and a ''[[Moonsault|No Laughing Matter]]'' to win the match. Morrus delivered the move again after the match.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nThe third match was a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types|tag team match]] for the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]. [[Chuck Palumbo]] and [[Sean O'Haire]] defended the titles against [[Mark Jindrak]] and [[Shawn Stasiak]]. Both teams were former members of the [[Natural Born Thrillers]]. After a back and forth action, Palumbo and O'Haire finished Stasiak when Palumbo delivered a ''[[Superkick|Jungle Kick]]'' and O\u2019Haire delivered a ''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#High-angle senton bomb|Seanton Bomb]]'' to win the match and retain the titles.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n[[Chavo Guerrero|Chavo Guerrero, Jr.]] defended the Cruiserweight Championship against [[Rey Mysterio|Rey Misterio, Jr.]] in the fourth match. Mysterio started the action with high paced quick and high-flying action. Both men traded moves until Guerrero brought a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Foreign object|steel chair]] into the ring and placed it in the corner. He tried to toss Mysterio into the cornered chair but Mysterio avoided the move and gained the momentum. Mysterio tried to close the match by hitting Guerrero with the chair following a [[DDT (professional wrestling)#Tornado DDT|Tornado DDT]] but the [[Referee (professional wrestling)|referee]] took it away. Guerrero took advantage of the referee's distraction and grabbed another chair, hitting Mysterio with it and delivering a [[Brainbuster]] to win the match and retain his title.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nIn the next match, [[Rick Steiner]] defended the [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Goldust|Dustin Rhodes]]. Steiner won the match by exposing a turnbuckle and slamming Rhodes face-first into the exposed turnbuckle and pinning him by putting his feet on ropes to gain leverage. As a result, Steiner retained his title. After the match, Steiner delivered a ''[[Professional wrestling throws#Death Valley|Steiner Driver]]'' and cut a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|promo]] before going for another post-match assault on Rhodes but Rhodes countered with a ''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Low blow|Shattered Dreams]]''.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nTotally Buffed ([[Lex Luger]] and [[Buff Bagwell]]) were scheduled to take on [[KroniK]] ([[Brian Adams (wrestler)|Brian Adams]] and [[Bryan Clark]]) in a tag team match to determine the #1 contenders for the World Tag Team Championship at Greed. However, Clark was injured before the match but appeared alongside Adams but Bagwell hit him with a steel chair to take him out of the match. Adams was left alone to fend off Totally Buffed, making it a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]]. Adams tried to control the early portion of the match but was dominated by his opponents due to number disadvantage. Adams made a comeback by [[powerslam]]ming Luger until [[Mike Awesome]] showed up and was disguised as Clark. He attacked Adams until Clark came to the ringside to brawl with Awesome in the aisle. Luger applied a ''[[Backbreaker#Argentine backbreaker rack|Torture Rack]]'' on Adams and Bagwell delivered a ''[[Neckbreaker#Flying neckbreaker|Buff Blockbuster]]'' to Adams to win the match and earn the title shot for the tag team titles.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n[[Lance Storm]] put his newly won position of [[Professional wrestling authority figures#Commissioner|WCW Commissioner]] against [[Ernest Miller]]. Miller started the match with his signature kicks until Storm began targeting his leg to slow the momentum. Miller attempted at a ''[[540 kick|Feliner]]'' but Storm countered with a [[Takedown (grappling)|single leg takedown]] and applied a ''[[Boston crab#Single leg Boston crab|Maple Leaf]]'' which Miller reversed and delivered an [[Professional wrestling attacks#Enzuigiri|enzuigiri]]. [[Mike Sanders (wrestler)|Mike Sanders]] appeared ringside to distract Miller, but Miller's [[Manager (professional wrestling)|valet]] [[The Nitro Girls|Miss Jones]] kicked him. Miller took advantage of the situation and hit a ''Feliner'' for the win and won the position of WCW Commissioner, which would be effective by mid-night. After the match, Miller was ejected by the arena as the position had not been effective yet.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\nThe final match on the undercard was [[Diamond Dallas Page]] versus [[Jeff Jarrett]]. However, Jarrett goaded Page into fighting [[Chris Kanyon]] into a match after a brawl between Page and Kanyon on that week's ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Nitro]]''. Kanyon launched a sneak attack on Page from behind but Page soon countered Kanyon's offensive. Both men exchanged moves until Kanyon tried to win by delivering a ''[[Cutter (professional wrestling)|Kanyon Kutter]]'' but got a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Near-fall|near-fall]]. Kanyon called Jarrett to hit Page with an ''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Guitar shot|Acoustic Equalizer]]'' but Jarrett missed it and Page took advantage with a [[Pin (professional wrestling)#Roll-up|roll-up]] but Kanyon kicked out at 2. The referee was knocked out and Jarrett entered the ring to hit Page with a ''[[Facebuster#Forward Russian legsweep|Stroke]]''. Kanyon followed it with a ''[[Facebuster#Reverse STO|Flatliner]]'' to win the match. After the match, Jarrett and Page began their match. Jarrett took advantage of Page's condition but Page managed to counter with a brawl at ringside. Page tried his ''[[Cutter (professional wrestling)|Diamond Cutter]]'' on Jarrett on the announce table but Jarrett shoved him into [[Tony Schiavone]]. Jarrett controlled the match until Page made a comeback near the closing moments of the match. Kanyon returned to the ring to pull Page out of the ring, allowing Jarrett to nail Page with a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Chair shot|chair shot]] and got a near-fall. Jarrett went for his ''Acoustic Equalizer'' on Page but he ducked and Kanyon was hit with it, allowing Page to deliver a ''Diamond Cutter'' to Jarrett to get the win.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n===Main event match===\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|loser leaves WCW match]] between [[Scott Steiner]] and [[Kevin Nash]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]. Nash won the title in just [[Squash (professional wrestling)|seventeen seconds]] by pinning Steiner after hitting him with a title belt. After the match, [[Ric Flair]] announced that the match was a [[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|two out of three falls match]] contested under [[Professional wrestling match types#No Disqualification match|no disqualification rules]], thus continuing the match. Diamond Dallas Page appeared at the ringside to help Nash in the situation but Totally Buffed came to the ringside to take him out of the equation. Steiner's bodyguard [[Melinda O'Hearn|Midajah]] interfered in the match and Steiner hit Nash with a steel pipe outside the ring. Steiner was unable to pick Nash and toss him into the ring, so Flair made it a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls count anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] and Steiner pinned Nash to win the second fall and even the score. The two men continued the action in the third fall. Flair handed a steel chair to Steiner and he hit Nash with it while Midajah held him. Steiner applied a ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Camel clutch|Steiner Recliner]]'' on Nash but Nash escaped it. He tossed Steiner into the corner with a [[Professional wrestling throws#Snake Eyes|Snake Eyes]] and a [[Professional wrestling attacks#Big boot|big boot]], followed by a ''[[Powerbomb#Release powerbomb|Jackknife Powerbomb]]''. Nash attempted a pinfall but the pinfall was broken up by Midajah. Nash delivered a [[Powerslam#Side slam|side slam]] to Midajah. Flair tossed another chair to Steiner, allowing Steiner to hit Nash with the chair and he applied a ''Steiner Recliner'' to knock out Nash to get the win and retain the title, thus forcing Nash to leave WCW.<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[Shane Helms]] got his title shot at the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WCW Cruiserweight Championship]] at [[Chavo Guerrero, Jr.]] at the [[WCW Greed|Greed]] pay-per-view, where he defeated Guerrero to win the title. Totally Buffed received their title shot at the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]] against [[Chuck Palumbo]] and [[Sean O'Haire]] at the event but failed to win the title. [[Diamond Dallas Page]] got a title shot for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]] against [[Scott Steiner]] due to interfering in Steiner's title match against Nash at SuperBrawl Revenge. Steiner defeated Page to retain the title in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls count anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] at Greed, but lost the title to [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] (who held the United States Championship) in a winner-take-all match on the final episode of ''WCW Monday Nitro'' on March 26, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/miscppv.html#greed|title=WCW Greed results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=2017-02-23}}</ref><ref name=play>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2005/06/22/1098665.html|title=Booker T to play two more years|author=Jason Clevett|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=April 17, 2008|date=June 22, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=\"411mania\"/><ref name=\"thehistoryofwwe\"/>\n|dark1=yes\n|match1=[[Chris Harris (wrestler)|Chris Harris]] defeated [[Kid Romeo]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=N/A\n|match2=[[Gregory Helms|Shane Helms]] defeated [[Evan Karagias]], [[Kaz Hayashi]], [[Jamie Noble|Jamie Knoble]], [[Shannon Moore]] and [[Jimmy Yang|Yun Yang]]\n|stip2=6 man [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|Elimination match]]\n|time2=17:30\n|match3=[[Bill DeMott|Hugh Morrus]] defeated [[Jerry Tuite|The Wall]]\n|stip3=Singles match\n|time3=09:43\n|match4=[[Sean O'Haire]] and [[Chuck Palumbo]] (c) defeated [[Mark Jindrak]] and [[Shawn Stasiak]]\n|stip4=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types|Tag team match]] for the [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]]\n|time4=11:37\n|match5=[[Chavo Guerrero Jr.]] (c) defeated [[Rey Mysterio|Rey Misterio Jr.]]\n|stip5=Singles match for the [[WWE Cruiserweight Championship (1991-2007)|WCW Cruiserweight Championship]]\n|time5=15:54\n|match6=[[Rick Steiner]] (c) defeated [[Goldust|Dustin Rhodes]]\n|stip6=Singles match for the [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time6=09:11\n|match7=Totally Buffed ([[Lex Luger]] and [[Buff Bagwell]]) defeated [[Brian Adams (wrestler)|Brian Adams]]\n|stip7=[[professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|Handicap match]]\n|time7=06:25\n|match8=[[Ernest Miller]] (with [[The Nitro Girls|Ms. Jones]]) defeated [[Lance Storm]]\n|stip8=Singles match for the position of WCW Commissioner\n|time8=08:07\n|match9=[[Chris Kanyon]] defeated [[Diamond Dallas Page]]\n|stip9=Singles match\n|time9=08:15\n|match10=Diamond Dallas Page defeated [[Jeff Jarrett]]\n|stip10=Singles match\n|time10=08:30\n|match11=[[Scott Steiner]] (c) (with [[Midajah]] and [[Ric Flair]]) defeated [[Kevin Nash]] 2\u20131\n|stip11=[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Two-out-of-three falls]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|\"loser leaves WCW\" match]] for the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]]\n|time11=11:04\n}}\n\n===No. 1 Contender's match eliminations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Elimination no.\n!Wrestler\n!Eliminated by\n!Elimination move\n!Time\n|-\n|1\n|Evan Karagias\n|Yun Yang\n|[[Neckbreaker]]\n|10:21\n|-\n|2\n|Yun Yang\n|Jamie Knoble\n|[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Reverse piledriver)|Jumping reverse piledriver]]\n|10:51\n|-\n|3\n|Jamie Knoble\n|Shannon Moore\n|''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving leg drop bulldog|Bottoms Up]]''\n|11:58\n|-\n|4\n|Shannon Moore\n|Shane Helms\n|''[[Professional wrestling attacks#Spinning headlock elbow drop|Nightmare on Helms Street]]''\n|15:11\n|-\n|5\n|Kaz Hayashi\n|Shane Helms\n|[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Vertebreaker|Vertebreaker]]\n|17:30\n|-\n!Winner:Billy Kidman\n|colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"#f2f2f2\"|Billy Kidman\n|}\n\n===Two out of three falls match results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Fall no.\n!Fall scoring move\n!Time\n|-\n|1\n|Nash pinned Steiner after hitting him with the [[Professional wrestling championship|title belt]]\n|00:17\n|-\n|2\n|Steiner pinned Nash after hitting him with a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Foreign object|steel pipe]]\n|02:47\n|-\n|3\n|Steiner hit Nash with a steel chair and won via knockout with a ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Camel clutch|Steiner Recliner]]''\n|11:04\n|-\n!Winner:\n|colspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"#f2f2f2\"|Scott Steiner\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2001 WCW pay-per-view events}}\n{{WCWPPV|SuperBrawl}}\n\n[[Category:SuperBrawl|SuperBrawl 11]]\n[[Category:Events in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:2001 in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:February 2001 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2001 World Championship Wrestling pay-per-view events]]\n", "name_user": "Crash Underride", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SuperBrawl_Revenge"}
{"title_page": "Kerbonn", "text_new": "'''Kerbonn''' is a village in the commune of [[Camaret-sur-Mer]] in France, between the [[pointe de Pen-Hir]] and the [[pointe du Toulinguet]], on the [[Crozon]] peninsula.  As well as its fortifications, the site also houses the ruins of the manor of Coecilian.\n\n==Kerbonn batteries==\nKerbonn's many fortifications form part of the defences of the [[goulet de Brest]].<ref name=mil>{{DionBrest}}</ref>  The first fortification on the site is a [[mortar (weapon)|mortar]] battery dating to 1889-1891, with its underground magazine. The Fort de Kerbonn is a side battery, designed to fire on ships in the [[roadstead of Brest]].  Another French battery was built in 1932, and between 1942 and 1944 the Germans built four [[casemate]]s on the site to house French 164mm guns, 6 air-raid shelters, one fire-direction post and three anti-aircraft-gun positions.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url        = http://patrimoine.region-bretagne.fr/main.xsp?execute=show_document&id=MERIMEEIA29001316\n |title      = Patrimoine architectural et mobilier en Bretagne / Inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral du patrimoine culturel\n |author     = \n |year       = 2006\n |publisher  = Conseil R\u00e9gional de Bretagne\n |accessdate = 2011-06-21\n}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  One of these German casemates now houses a memorial to the [[Battle of the Atlantic]].\n\n== Notes  ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://patrimoine.region-bretagne.fr/main.xsp?execute=show_document&id=MERIMEEIA29001316 Position de Kerbonn]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral)\n* [http://www.fortiff.be/iff/index.php?p=258  Batteries of Kerbonn]  (photos)\n* [https://archive.is/20130213132610/http://patrimoine.region-bretagne.fr/main.xsp?execute=show_document&id=MERIMEEIA29001553 Manor of Coecilian] (photos)\n\n{{coord|48|16|9|N|4|36|58|W|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Fortifications of Brest, France]]\n[[Category:Villages in Brittany]]\n", "text_old": "'''Kerbonn''' is a village in the commune of [[Camaret-sur-Mer]] in France, between the [[pointe de Pen-Hir]] and the [[pointe du Toulinguet]], on the [[Crozon]] peninsula.  As well as its fortifications, the site also houses the ruins of the manor of Coecilian.\n\n==Kerbonn batteries==\nKerbonn's many fortifications form part of the defences of the [[goulet de Brest]].<ref name=mil>{{DionBrest}}</ref>  The first fortification on the site is a [[mortar (weapon)|mortar]] battery dating to 1889-1891, with its underground magazine. The Fort de Kerbonn is a side battery, designed to fire on ships in the [[roadstead of Brest]].  Another French battery was built in 1932, and between 1942 and 1944 the Germans built four [[casemate]]s on the site to house French 164mm guns, 6 air-raid shelters, one fire-direction post and three anti-aircraft-gun positions.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url        = http://patrimoine.region-bretagne.fr/main.xsp?execute=show_document&id=MERIMEEIA29001316\n |title      = Patrimoine architectural et mobilier en Bretagne / Inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral du patrimoine culturel\n |author     = \n |year       = 2006\n |publisher  = Conseil R\u00e9gional de Bretagne\n |accessdate = 2011-06-21\n}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  One of these German casemates now houses a memorial to the [[Battle of the Atlantic]].\n\n== Notes  ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://patrimoine.region-bretagne.fr/main.xsp?execute=show_document&id=MERIMEEIA29001316 Position de Kerbonn]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral)\n* [http://www.fortiff.be/iff/index.php?p=258  Batteries of Kerbonn]  (photos)\n* [https://archive.is/20130213132610/http://patrimoine.region-bretagne.fr/main.xsp?execute=show_document&id=MERIMEEIA29001553 Manor of Coecilian] (photos)\n\n{{coord|48|16|9|N|4|36|58|W|type:landmark_region:FR|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Fortifications of Brest, France]]\n[[Category:Villages in Brittany]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerbonn"}
{"title_page": "Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub\n| series       = [[South Park]]\n| image        =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[Image:South Park Hot Tub.jpg|250px]] -->\n| caption      = Randy and Gerald in the hot tub.\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 8\n| airdate      = July 21, 1999\n| production   = 308\n| writer       = Trey Parker<br/>[[Matt Stone]]<br/>David Goodman\n| director     = [[Trey Parker]]\n| guests       = \n| season_article = South Park (season 3)\n| episode_list = List of South Park episodes\n| season_list  = \n| prev         = [[Cat Orgy]]\n| next         = [[Jewbilee]]\n}}\n\"'''Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub'''\" (also known as \"'''Melvins'''\") is the eighth episode of the [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] of the American animated television series ''[[South Park]]'', and the 39th episode of the series overall. The episode is the second part of The Meteor Shower Trilogy, and centers upon third grader [[Stan Marsh]] and his father [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|Randy]]. It premiered on [[Comedy Central]] on July 21, 1999. \n\nThe episode was written by series creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]], and David Goodman. It is noted for being the first episode in which [[Butters Stotch]] serves as an important supporting character, with substantial dialogue.<ref name=Ranker>Abraham, Chris. [https://www.ranker.com/list/best-butters-episodes-of-south-park/chris-abraham \"Ranking Every Butters Episode of South Park Best to Worst\"]. [[Ranker]]. Retrieved June 21, 2018.</ref> \n\n==Plot==\nAfter dropping [[Shelly Marsh|Shelly]] off at [[Cat Orgy|Cartman's home]], [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|the Marshes]] and [[Stan Marsh|Stan]] are off to a [[party]] at the home of [[Mr. Mackey]]. Stan is upset that he has to go and becomes even more angered when he is locked in a room with nerdy \"Melvin\" classmates that he does not like: [[List of students at South Park Elementary#Pip Pirrup|Pip]], [[Butters Stotch|Butters]], and [[Dougie (South Park)|Dougie]]. After finding a box of women's clothing the three insist on playing ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', and an unenthusiastic Stan uses the game to find a way out of the basement to an upstairs bedroom where there are cookies and TV. Meanwhile, at the party, Mr. Mackey gives [[Gerald and Shiela Broflovski|the Broflovskis]] and [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|Marshes]] a tour of his home and leads them out to the [[hot tub]]. The wives leave Randy and Gerald outside in the hot tub, who declare the present evening to be a night of experimenting. The two talk about [[threesomes]] and decide to [[masturbate]] in front of one another. This leads to awkwardness after Randy questions his sexuality.\n\nThe [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] thinks that the party inside is a [[mass suicide|suicide cult]], and that they plan to kill themselves at the start of the meteor shower. Determined to prevent this, they set up a blockade and prepare to open fire on the cult if they do not desist; at one point, a couple of party-goers leave and are immediately fatally shot at (due to the ATF believing they had weapons despite them clearly not having any). The Newsman recalls that the last time the ATF did this was at the [[Waco siege]] where they ended up killing innocent people for false accusation, but the ATF dismisses him. All the while, the party-goers (who progressively become drunk) inside are unaware of their presence. Stan and the kids discover what is happening and try to speak to the ATF, but are shot at and forced to flee back inside. The kids record a [[video tape]] showing that the party inside is not a cult to the Newsman; the ATF realizes their mistake, claiming it was a \"test simulation\" and quickly disperse after their secret weapon, a large rocket called \"The Negotiator\", fires and destroys every home in the neighborhood except for Mackey's. \n\nInside, Randy is extremely uncomfortable being around Gerald, who is concerned about Randy's behavior. When Randy finally admits to the entire party that he and Gerald engaged in group masturbation, he is relieved upon discovering that he's not the only one to have masturbated in front of a person of the same sex. Outside, the boys rejoice their triumph of saving the day and Stan realizes that the others are just normal kids like him. All is immediately forgotten, however, when [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] returns from [[Jewbilee]] camp and Stan goes back to his old ways, telling Kyle that he had to \"spend the evening with these friggin' Melvins\".\n\nThe credits roll with a parody version of [[Cher]]'s \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" (which the ATF used to drown out the party-goers in an effort for them to submit, unaware that Mackey was playing the same song and which everyone enjoyed).\n\n==Production==\nTrey and Matt based much of the plot, including the ATF's use of Cher, on the [[Waco siege]] after watching the documentary [[Waco: The Rules of Engagement]]. [[Pam Brady]] provided the voice for Cher.<ref name=\"commentary\">{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]], [[Matt Stone|Stone, Matt]]|date = November 2002|title=South Park: The Complete Third Season: \"Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub\" ''(Audio commentary)'' |medium= DVD|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s03e08-two-guys-naked-in-a-hot-tub Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub] Full Episode at South Park Studios\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/guide/episodes/s03e08-two-guys-naked-in-a-hot-tub Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub] Episode guide at South Park Studios\n* {{IMDb episode|0705980}}\n* {{Tv.com episode|2455}}\n\n{{South Park episodes|3}}\n\n[[Category:1999 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives in fiction]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related South Park episodes]]\n[[Category:Masturbation in fiction]]\n[[Category:South Park (season 3) episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub\n| series       = [[South Park]]\n| image        =<!-- Deleted image removed:  [[Image:South Park Hot Tub.jpg|250px]] -->\n| caption      = Randy and Gerald in the hot tub.\n| season       = 3\n| episode      = 8\n| airdate      = July 21, 1999\n| production   = 308\n| writer       = Trey Parker<br/>[[Matt Stone]]<br/>David Goodman\n| director     = [[Trey Parker]]\n| guests       = \n| season_article = South Park (season 3)\n| episode_list = List of South Park episodes\n| season_list  = \n| prev         = [[Cat Orgy]]\n| next         = [[Jewbilee]]\n}}\n\"'''Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub'''\" (also known as \"'''Melvins'''\") is the eighth episode of the [[South Park (season 3)|third season]] of the American animated television series ''[[South Park]]'', and the 39th episode of the series overall. The episode is the second part of The Meteor Shower Trilogy, and centers upon third grader [[Stan Marsh]] and his father [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|Randy]]. It premiered on [[Comedy Central]] on July 21, 1999. \n\nThe episode was written by series creators [[Trey Parker]] and [[Matt Stone]], and David Goodman. It is noted for being the first episode in which [[Butters Stotch]] serves as an important supporting character, with substantial dialogue.<ref name=Ranker>Abraham, Chris. [https://www.ranker.com/list/best-butters-episodes-of-south-park/chris-abraham \"Ranking Every Butters Episode of South Park Best to Worst\"]. [[Ranker]]. Retrieved June 21, 2018.</ref> \n\n==Plot==\nAfter dropping [[Shelly Marsh|Shelly]] off at [[Cat Orgy|Cartman's home]], [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|the Marshes]] and [[Stan Marsh|Stan]] are off to a [[party]] at the home of [[Mr. Mackey]]. Stan is upset that he has to go and becomes even more angered when he is locked in a room with nerdy \"Melvin\" classmates that he does not like: [[List of students at South Park Elementary#Pip Pirrup|Pip]], [[Butters Stotch|Butters]], and [[Dougie (South Park)|Dougie]]. After finding a box of women's clothing the three insist on playing ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', and an unenthusiastic Stan uses the game to find a way out of the basement to an upstairs bedroom where there are cookies and TV. Meanwhile, at the party, Mr. Mackey gives [[Gerald and Shiela Broflovski|the Broflovskis]] and [[Randy and Sharon Marsh|Marshes]] a tour of his home and leads them out to the [[hot tub]]. The wives leave Randy and Gerald outside in the hot tub, who declare the present evening to be a night of experimenting. The two talk about [[threesomes]] and decide to [[masturbate]] in front of one another. This leads to awkwardness after Randy questions his sexuality.\n\nThe [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] thinks that the party inside is a [[mass suicide|suicide cult]], and that they plan to kill themselves at the start of the meteor shower. Determined to prevent this, they set up a blockade and prepare to open fire on the cult if they do not desist; at one point, a couple of party-goers leave and are immediately fatally shot at (due to the ATF believing they had weapons despite them clearly not having any). The Newsman recalls that the last time the ATF did this was at the [[Waco siege]] where they ended up killing innocent people for false accusation, but the ATF dismisses him. All the while, the party-goers (who progressively become drunk) inside are unaware of their presence. Stan and the kids discover what is happening and try to speak to the ATF, but are shot at and forced to flee back inside. The kids record a [[video tape]] showing that the party inside is not a cult to the Newsman; the ATF realizes their mistake, claiming it was a \"test simulation\" and quickly disperse after their secret weapon, a large rocket called \"The Negotiator\", fires and destroys every home in the neighborhood except for Mackey's. \n\nInside, Randy is extremely uncomfortable being around Gerald, who is concerned about Randy's behavior. When Randy finally admits to the entire party that he and Gerald engaged in group masturbation, he is relieved upon discovering that he's not the only one to have masturbated in front of a person of the same sex. Outside, the boys rejoice their triumph of saving the day and Stan realizes that the others are just normal kids like him. All is immediately forgotten, however, when [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] returns from [[Jewbilee]] camp and Stan goes back to his old ways, telling Kyle that he had to \"spend the evening with these friggin' Melvins\".\n\nThe credits roll with a parody version of [[Cher]]'s \"[[Believe (Cher song)|Believe]]\" (which the ATF used to drown out the party-goers in an effort for them to submit, unaware that Mackey was playing the same song and which everyone enjoyed).\n\n==Production==\n Trey and Matt based much of the plot, including the ATF's use of Cher, on the [[Waco siege]] after watching the documentary [[Waco: The Rules of Engagement]]. [[Pam Brady]] provided the voice for Cher.<ref name=\"commentary\">{{Cite video | people=[[Trey Parker|Parker, Trey]], [[Matt Stone|Stone, Matt]]|date = November 2002|title=South Park: The Complete Third Season: \"Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub\" ''(Audio commentary)'' |medium= DVD|publisher=[[Paramount Pictures#Paramount Home Entertainment|Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/full-episodes/s03e08-two-guys-naked-in-a-hot-tub Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub] Full Episode at South Park Studios\n* [http://www.southparkstudios.com/guide/episodes/s03e08-two-guys-naked-in-a-hot-tub Two Guys Naked in a Hot Tub] Episode guide at South Park Studios\n* {{IMDb episode|0705980}}\n* {{Tv.com episode|2455}}\n\n{{South Park episodes|3}}\n\n[[Category:1999 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives in fiction]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related South Park episodes]]\n[[Category:Masturbation in fiction]]\n[[Category:South Park (season 3) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "ErieSwiftByrd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two_Guys_Naked_in_a_Hot_Tub"}
{"title_page": "List of churches in the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco", "text_new": "[[File:St Mary's Cathedral - San Francisco.jpg|right|thumb|250px|[[Cathedral of Saint Mary of the Assumption (San Francisco, California)|Cathedral of Saint Mary of the Assumption]], completed in 1971]]\nThis is a list of current and former [[Roman Catholicism in the United States|Roman Catholic]] churches in the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco]]. The Archdiocese of San Francisco includes the [[San Francisco, California|City and County of San Francisco]] and the Counties of [[Marin County, California|Marin]] and [[San Mateo County, California|San Mateo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Parish Finder|publisher=Archdiocese of San Francisco|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url=https://sfarchdiocese.org/parishfinder?query=marin&#37;20county}}</ref> \n\nThe [[mother church]] of the Archdiocese is the [[Cathedral of Saint Mary of the Assumption (San Francisco, California)|Cathedral of Saint Mary of the Assumption]], completed in 1971 in the [[Cathedral Hill, San Francisco|Cathedral Hill]] neighborhood of San Francisco. It replaced the original [[Old Saint Mary's Cathedral]] which now functions as a parish church.  The archdiocese also includes many other historic churches including [[Mission San Francisco de As\u00eds]], the oldest building in San Francisco, and [[Saints Peter and Paul Church, San Francisco|Saints Peter and Paul Church]], known as the Italian cathedral of the West.\n\n==San Francisco County==\n===Deanery 1===\nDeanery 1 consists of San Francisco's [[Sunset District]], Forest Hill, Parkside, Westwood Park, and Lakeside neighborhoods.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''\n|-\n|[[Holy Name of Jesus Church in San Francisco|Holy Name of Jesus]]\n|[[File:Holy Name of Jesus Church (San Francisco).jpg|100px]]\n|1555 39th Avenue\n|Parish created in 1925 in the [[Sunset District]]; the current modern concrete and steel church was dedicated in 1964 and was referred to at the time as being \"as modern as tomorrow\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Church History|publisher=Holy Name of Jesus Parish|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://holynamesf.org/index.php/about/church-history}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Anne of the Sunset Church in San Francisco|St. Anne of the Sunset]]\n|[[File:St. Anne of the Sunset.jpg|100px]]\n|850 Judah St.\n|Romanesque church in [[Sunset District]] completed in 1932\n|-\n|[[St. Brendan Church in San Francisco|St. Brendan the Navigator]]\n|\n|29 Rockaway Ave.\n|California mission-style structure with a distinctive bell tower<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=St. Brendan the Navigator Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://www.stbrendanparish.org/}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St. Cecilia Church in San Francisco|St. Cecilia]]\n|\n|2555 17th Ave\n|Parish created in 1917; current Spanish colonial church completed in 1956 in [[Sunset District]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Saint Ceclia Parish History|publisher=Saint Cecilia Catholic Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://stcecilia.com/parish-life/about}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Finn Barr\n|\n|415 Edna Street\n|Parish created in 1926 in the Sunnyside district<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Our Parish|publisher=St. Finn Barr Catholic Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://sfbsf.org/}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Gabriel\n|\n|2559 40th Avenue\n|Parish established in 1941; church dedicated in 1942<ref>{{cite web|title=History of St. Gabriel|publisher=St. Gabriel Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.sgparish.org/history.html}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. John of God\n|\n|1290 5th Ave\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=St. John of God Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.sjog.net/}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Stephen\n|\n|601 Eucalyptus Dr\n|Parish formed in 1950; new church dedicated in 1964<ref>{{cite web|title=Excerpt from \"Saint Stephen Parish Celebrates Fifty Years\"|publisher=Saint Stephen Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.saintstephensf.org/our-history.php}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Thomas More\n|\n|1300 Junipero Serra Blvd\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=St. Thomas More Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://stmchurch.com/}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Deanery 2===\nDeanery 2 consists of the [[Bayview-Hunters Point, San Francisco|Bayview/Hunter's Point]] neighborhood, and the [[Excelsior District]], [[Visitacion Valley]], and [[Crocker Amazon]], and Ingleside areas.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''\n|-\n|All Hallows Chapel\n|\t\n|1400 Newhall St\n|Historic church located on a hill overlooking [[Bayview\u2013Hunters Point, San Francisco|Hunters Point]]; now merged into the Our Lady of Lourdes parish<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Our Church|publisher=Our Lady of Lourdes - All Hallows Catholic Community|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.ourladyoflourdescatholicsf.org/history}}</ref>\n|-\n|Corpus Christi\n|\n|62 Santa Rosa Ave\n|A Salesian parish<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=Corpus Christi Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://corpuschristisf.org/}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Church of the Epiphany in San Francisco|Church of the Epiphany]]\n|\n|827 Vienna St\n|Current church completed in 1950<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Our Parish|publisher=Church of the Epiphany|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://epiphanysf.com/history}}</ref>\n|-\n|Our Lady of Lourdes\n|\n|410 Hawes St\n|Wooden chapel with carved beams and stained glass windows depicting Martin Luther King, Jr., Sojourner Truth and others<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Our Church|publisher=Our Lady of Lourdes - All Hallows Catholic Community|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.ourladyoflourdescatholicsf.org/history}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Elizabeth\n|\n|459 Somerset St\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=St. Elizabeth Church of San Francisco|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.stelizabethsf.org/}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Emydius\n|\n|286 Ashton Ave\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Home page|publisher=St. Emydius Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://www.stemydius-sf.org/}}</ref>\n|-\n|St. Michael Korean\n|\n|32 Broad St\n|\n|-\n|St. Paul of the Shipwreck\n|\n|1122 Jamestown Ave\n|Parish founded in 1915 in the Bayview Hunters Point neighborhood<ref>{{cite web|title=Who We Are|publisher=St. Paul of the Shipwreck Catholic Church|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=https://www.stpauloftheshipwreck.org/about-us}}</ref>\n|-\n|Church of the Visitacion\n|\n|655 Sunnydale Ave\n|Parish history dates to 1907; current church dedicated in 1952<ref>{{cite web|title=History of the Church of the Visitacion: 1907 to Present|publisher=Church of Visitacion Catholic Inclusive Community|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url=http://www.visitacionchurch.org/history.html}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Deanery 3===\nDeanery 3 consists of the [[Western Addition]], [[Japantown]], [[The Castro]], [[Haight-Ashbury]], [[Richmond District, San Francisco, California|Richmond District]], and [[Cow Hollow, San Francisco|Cow Hollow]] neighborhoods.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:75%\"\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Name'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"10%\" |'''Image'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"25%\" |'''Location'''\n! style=\"background:darkviolet; color:yellow;\" width=\"15\" |'''Description/Notes'''