es in California]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reference list duplication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_churches_in_the_Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_San_Francisco"}
{"title_page": "Keitum", "text_new": "{{about|the village in Germany|the village in Mizoram state of India|Kei\u1e6dum}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox German location\n|name              = Keitum\n|image_photo       = KeitumFriesenhaus1784.jpg\n|image_caption     = 18th-century ''Friesenhaus'' in Keitum\n|coordinates       = {{coord|54|36|N|8|22|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = \n|state        = Schleswig-Holstein\n|district             = Nordfriesland\n|type               = ''Ortsteil'' \n|Town              = ''[[Sylt (municipality)|Gemeinde Sylt]]''\n|elevation              = \n|area            = \n|population         = \n|Stand             = \n|postal_code               = \n|area_code           = 04651\n|licence               = NF\n|NUTS              = \n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = \n|Adresse-Verband   = \n|website           = [http://www.gemeinde-sylt.de/ www.gemeinde-sylt.de]\n|mayor     = Nikolas H\u00e4ckel <br> \"Gemeinde Sylt\"\n}}\n\n'''Keitum''' (Danish: ''Kejtum'', North Frisian: ''Kairem'') is a village on the [[North Sea]] island of [[Sylt]] in the district of [[Nordfriesland]] in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]]. Today, it is an ''Ortsteil'' of the ''[[Sylt (municipality)|Gemeinde Sylt]]''.\n\n==Etymology==\nIt is unclear from what the name Keitum (''Kairem'' in North Frisian, ''Kejtum'' in Danish) is derived. One theory posits that it used to refer to the \"home of Kei\" or \"home of Keit\". Alternatively, it could be based on \"Heidum\" (''auf der Heide'' or \"on the heath\").<ref name=\"Lex\">{{cite book|last1=Kunz|first1=Harry|last2=Steensen|first2=Thomas|title=Taschenlexikon Sylt (German)|publisher=Wachholtz|year=2014|isbn=978-3-529-05525-6| page=}}</ref>{{rp|189}}\n\n==History==\n\"Keytum\" was first mentioned in 1462. Until the end of the 19th century, Keitum was the most important town on the island of Sylt. Since 1612 it was the location of Sylt's largest mill. In 1695, the village had 78 houses. A school house was built in 1763. In 1820, the harbour was expanded. Although keeping the navigation channel open was a continuing problem, Keitum harbour was the main connection between Sylt and the mainland until around 1867. After 1859, the harbour silted up and the ferry traffic shifted to Munkmarsch. In 1860, Keitum had passed Morsum as the island's most populous village (with 785 inhabitants). In the 1890s, the tourist business moved increasingly to [[Westerland, Germany|Westerland]], sidelining the eastern villages. Although Keitum is located on the railway which connected Westerland with Nieb\u00fcll via the [[Hindenburgdamm]] in 1927, most visitors disembarked only at the line's terminus, at Westerland.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|189\u2013190}}\n\n==Geography==\nKeitum is located on the [[Wadden Sea]] side of the island. The village fronts on the sea at what is called the ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Gr\u00fcnes Kliff|de}}'' (green cliff), a mostly vegetation-covered (hence green) escarpment.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|189}} It stretches along the coast for around 3 kilometres from the eastern edge of the village to the church of St. Severin, north of the village.\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2013, Keitum had a permanent population of around 880. Another 900 people have second homes in the village.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|188\u2013189}}\n\n==Economy==\nLike elsewhere on Sylt, tourism is a major industry. Since 1950, the village has held the status of ''Luftkurort'' (climatic spa). Keitum is known for its large number of traditional [[Uthland-Frisian house]]s, many of them over 200 years old, and its tree-lined avenues. Although the original [[elm trees]] died in the 1990s, they have been replaced by chestnut and linden trees. In addition, many craftspeople (like gold smiths, weavers and potters) are based in Keitum.\n<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|189\u2013190}}\n\n==Attractions==\n===St. Severin===\n[[File:Severinskirche Keitum.jpg|thumb|St. Severin]]\n{{Main|St. Severin, Keitum}}\nOriginally built in the early 13th century, this [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] church is today thought to be the oldest in Schleswig-Holstein. It was originally dedicated to  the saints [[Canute IV of Denmark|Canute]] and Ketel, but later rededicated to [[Severin of Cologne]].<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|330}}\n\nThe attached graveyard holds the graves of numerous important local families (especially whalers and other owners or masters of ships) and of some notable people: [[Rudolf Augstein]], [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der (CDU)|Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Uwe Dallmeier|de}}, [[Peter Suhrkamp]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Ernst Mollenhauer|de}}. Several works of sculpture art have also been erected in the churchyard.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|332}}\n\n===Harhoog===\n[[File:Megalithic grave Harhoog in Keitum, Sylt, Germany.jpg|thumb|The megalithic tomb]]\n{{Main|Harhoog}}\nA [[megalithic tomb]], moved to its present location on the edge of Keitum in 1954 from its original position between Keitum and Tinnum, due to the construction of Sylt Airport.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|147}}\n\nLocated next to Harhoog is the [[Bronze Age]] [[tumulus]] ''Tipkenhoog''. Excavations of the mound in 1870 failed to locate any contents. In World War II, an observation post was situated on the hill, damaging the site.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|396}}\n\n===Further attractions===\nKeitum has three museums: ''Altfriesische Haus'', ''Sylter Heimatmuseum'' and the ''Feuerwehrmuseum''. The former is a house built in 1739 and mostly retains period furniture and accessoires, exhibiting 18th century home decor and living styles. The Heimatmuseum is located in a house dating from 1759 and features exhibits on local history and regional living conditions in the past.<ref name=Museen>{{cite web|url=http://www.museen-sh.de/Museum/DE-MUS-074511|title=Altfriesisches Haus (Sylt) (German)|publisher=Museen in SH|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gemeinde1>{{cite web|url=http://www.gemeinde-sylt.de/Freizeit-Kultur/altfriesisches-haus.html|title=Altfriesisches Haus (German)|publisher=Gemeinde Sylt|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gemeinde2>{{cite web|url=http://www.gemeinde-sylt.de/Freizeit-Kultur/heimatmuseum.html|title=Sylter Heimatmuseum (German)|publisher=Gemeinde Sylt|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n{{Main|Sylt (municipality)}}\nIn the ''Gebietsreform'' of 1970, Keitum became part of the newly created municipality [[Sylt-Ost]]. It used to be the seat of Sylt-Ost's municipal administration and also of that of the ''[[Amt (administrative division)|Amt]] [[Landschaft Sylt]]''. Sylt-Ost was merged on 1 January 2009 with [[Rantum]] and the town of [[Westerland, Germany|Westerland]]. In separate referendums in 2008, Westerland (by a large majority) and Sylt-Ost (narrowly) agreed to the merger in May 2008. Rantum followed. In September 2008, the merger contract was signed.<ref name=Merger>{{cite web|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/region/norddeutschland/article106764952/Die-Metropole-der-Insel-heisst-jetzt-Sylt.html|title=Die Metropole der Insel hei\u00dft jetzt Sylt (German)|publisher=Hamburger Abendblatt|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|16}}\n\nKeitum is now an ''Ortsteil'' of ''Gemeinde Sylt''. Since 1 May 2015, the mayor of ''Gemeinde Sylt'' has been Nikolas H\u00e4ckel. The administrations of both ''Gemeinde Sylt'' and ''Landschaft Sylt'' are today located in Westerland.\n\n===''Keitum-Therme''===\n[[File:Keitum-Therme.JPG|thumb|Ruins of Keitum-Therme in 2012]]\nIn a prominent site on the Keitum waterfront sits the large unfinished concrete ruin of a spa with indoor and outdoor pools - an example for a failed [[Public private partnership]]. Work on the ''Keitum-Therme'' started in 2007 but stopped in 2008, after disagreement between the municipality Sylt-Ost and the builder, leaving the facility half-finished. Due to water and frost damage, the condition of the ruins has long deteriorated past the point at which work could be economically resumed. However, plans to demolish the structures have been blocked by lawsuits about the bankruptcy of the development company.<ref name=therme1>{{cite web|url=http://www.shz.de/lokales/sylter-rundschau/verhandlungen-ueber-thermenruine-gehen-in-naechste-runde-id8625221.html|title=Verhandlungen \u00fcber Thermenruine gehen in die n\u00e4chste Runde (German)|publisher=Sylter Rundschau|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Therme2>{{cite web|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/region/article108767301/Keitum-Therme-Sylt-wird-teuerste-Ruine-nicht-los.html|title=Keitum-Therme - Sylt wird die teuerste Ruine nicht los (German)|publisher=Hamburger Abendblatt|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transport===\nKeitum has a railway station on the line between [[Westerland, Germany|Westerland]] and [[Nieb\u00fcll]]. However, long-distance trains and the ''Sylt Shuttle'' do not stop there. But hourly, there is a direct connection by train to Hamburg-Altona.\n\n==Notable people==\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Christian Peter Hansen|de}}, local historian (1803\u20131879)\n* [[Gustav Jenner]], composer and conductor (1865\u20131920)\n* [[Boy Lornsen]], sculptor and author of children's literature (1922\u20131995)\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Uwe Jens Lornsen|de}}, civil servant and symbolic figure for a unified Schleswig-Holstein (1793\u20131838)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.insel-sylt.de/orte/keitum.html Keitum tourist office]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Schleswig-Holstein]]\n[[Category:Sylt]]\n[[Category:Nordfriesland]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the village in Germany|the village in Mizoram state of India|Kei\u1e6dum}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox German location\n|name              = Keitum\n|image_photo       = KeitumFriesenhaus1784.jpg\n|image_caption     = 18th-century ''Friesenhaus'' in Keitum\n|coordinates       = {{coord|54|36|N|8|22|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = \n|state        = Schleswig-Holstein\n|district             = Nordfriesland\n|type               = ''Ortsteil'' \n|Town              = ''[[Sylt (municipality)|Gemeinde Sylt]]''\n|elevation              = \n|area            = \n|population         = \n|Stand             = \n|postal_code               = \n|area_code           = 04651\n|licence               = NF\n|NUTS              = \n|Gemeindeschl\u00fcssel = \n|Adresse-Verband   = \n|website           = [http://www.gemeinde-sylt.de/ www.gemeinde-sylt.de]\n|mayor     = Nikolas H\u00e4ckel <br> \"Gemeinde Sylt\"\n}}\n\n'''Keitum''' (Danish: ''Kejtum'', North Frisian: ''Kairem'') is a village on the [[North Sea]] island of [[Sylt]] in the district of [[Nordfriesland]] in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], [[Germany]]. Today, it is an ''Ortsteil'' of the ''[[Sylt (municipality)|Gemeinde Sylt]]''.  \n\n==Etymology==\nIt is unclear from what the name Keitum (''Kairem'' in North Frisian, ''Kejtum'' in Danish) is derived. One theory posits that it used to refer to the \"home of Kei\" or \"home of Keit\". Alternatively, it could be based on \"Heidum\" (''auf der Heide'' or \"on the heath\").<ref name=\"Lex\">{{cite book|last1=Kunz|first1=Harry|last2=Steensen|first2=Thomas|title=Taschenlexikon Sylt (German)|publisher=Wachholtz|year=2014|isbn=978-3-529-05525-6| page=}}</ref>{{rp|189}}\n\n==History==\n\"Keytum\" was first mentioned in 1462. Until the end of the 19th century, Keitum was the most important town on the island of Sylt. Since 1612 it was the location of Sylt's largest mill. In 1695, the village had 78 houses. A school house was built in 1763. In 1820, the harbour was expanded. Although keeping the navigation channel open was a continuing problem, Keitum harbour was the main connection between Sylt and the mainland until around 1867. After 1859, the harbour silted up and the ferry traffic shifted to Munkmarsch. In 1860, Keitum had passed Morsum as the island's most populous village (with 785 inhabitants). In the 1890s, the tourist business moved increasingly to [[Westerland, Germany|Westerland]], sidelining the eastern villages. Although Keitum is located on the railway which connected Westerland with Nieb\u00fcll via the [[Hindenburgdamm]] in 1927, most visitors disembarked only at the line's terminus, at Westerland.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|189-190}}  \n\n==Geography==\nKeitum is located on the [[Wadden Sea]] side of the island. The village fronts on the sea at what is called the ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Gr\u00fcnes Kliff|de}}'' (green cliff), a mostly vegetation-covered (hence green) escarpment.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|189}} It stretches along the coast for around 3 kilometres from the eastern edge of the village to the church of St. Severin, north of the village.\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2013, Keitum had a permanent population of around 880. Another 900 people have second homes in the village.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|188-189}}\n\n==Economy==\nLike elsewhere on Sylt, tourism is a major industry. Since 1950, the village has held the status of ''Luftkurort'' (climatic spa). Keitum is known for its large number of traditional [[Uthland-Frisian house]]s, many of them over 200 years old, and its tree-lined avenues. Although the original [[elm trees]] died in the 1990s, they have been replaced by chestnut and linden trees. In addition, many craftspeople (like gold smiths, weavers and potters) are based in Keitum.\n<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|189-190}}\n\n==Attractions==\n===St. Severin===\n[[File:Severinskirche Keitum.jpg|thumb|St. Severin]]\n{{Main|St. Severin, Keitum}}\nOriginally built in the early 13th century, this [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] church is today thought to be the oldest in Schleswig-Holstein. It was originally dedicated to  the saints [[Canute IV of Denmark|Canute]] and Ketel, but later rededicated to [[Severin of Cologne]].<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|330}} \n\nThe attached graveyard holds the graves of numerous important local families (especially whalers and other owners or masters of ships) and of some notable people: [[Rudolf Augstein]], [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der (CDU)|Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Uwe Dallmeier|de}}, [[Peter Suhrkamp]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Ernst Mollenhauer|de}}. Several works of sculpture art have also been erected in the churchyard.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|332}}\n\n===Harhoog===\n[[File:Megalithic grave Harhoog in Keitum, Sylt, Germany.jpg|thumb|The megalithic tomb]]\n{{Main|Harhoog}}\nA [[megalithic tomb]], moved to its present location on the edge of Keitum in 1954 from its original position between Keitum and Tinnum, due to the construction of Sylt Airport.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|147}}\n\nLocated next to Harhoog is the [[Bronze Age]] [[tumulus]] ''Tipkenhoog''. Excavations of the mound in 1870 failed to locate any contents. In World War II, an observation post was situated on the hill, damaging the site.<ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|396}}\n\n===Further attractions===\nKeitum has three museums: ''Altfriesische Haus'', ''Sylter Heimatmuseum'' and the ''Feuerwehrmuseum''. The former is a house built in 1739 and mostly retains period furniture and accessoires, exhibiting 18th century home decor and living styles. The Heimatmuseum is located in a house dating from 1759 and features exhibits on local history and regional living conditions in the past.<ref name=Museen>{{cite web|url=http://www.museen-sh.de/Museum/DE-MUS-074511|title=Altfriesisches Haus (Sylt) (German)|publisher=Museen in SH|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gemeinde1>{{cite web|url=http://www.gemeinde-sylt.de/Freizeit-Kultur/altfriesisches-haus.html|title=Altfriesisches Haus (German)|publisher=Gemeinde Sylt|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Gemeinde2>{{cite web|url=http://www.gemeinde-sylt.de/Freizeit-Kultur/heimatmuseum.html|title=Sylter Heimatmuseum (German)|publisher=Gemeinde Sylt|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n{{Main|Sylt (municipality)}}\nIn the ''Gebietsreform'' of 1970, Keitum became part of the newly created municipality [[Sylt-Ost]]. It used to be the seat of Sylt-Ost's municipal administration and also of that of the ''[[Amt (administrative division)|Amt]] [[Landschaft Sylt]]''. Sylt-Ost was merged on 1 January 2009 with [[Rantum]] and the town of [[Westerland, Germany|Westerland]]. In separate referendums in 2008, Westerland (by a large majority) and Sylt-Ost (narrowly) agreed to the merger in May 2008. Rantum followed. In September 2008, the merger contract was signed.<ref name=Merger>{{cite web|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/region/norddeutschland/article106764952/Die-Metropole-der-Insel-heisst-jetzt-Sylt.html|title=Die Metropole der Insel hei\u00dft jetzt Sylt (German)|publisher=Hamburger Abendblatt|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Lex\"/>{{rp|16}}\n\nKeitum is now an ''Ortsteil'' of ''Gemeinde Sylt''. Since 1 May 2015, the mayor of ''Gemeinde Sylt'' has been Nikolas H\u00e4ckel. The administrations of both ''Gemeinde Sylt'' and ''Landschaft Sylt'' are today located in Westerland.\n\n===''Keitum-Therme''===\n[[File:Keitum-Therme.JPG|thumb|Ruins of Keitum-Therme in 2012]]\nIn a prominent site on the Keitum waterfront sits the large unfinished concrete ruin of a spa with indoor and outdoor pools - an example for a failed [[Public private partnership]]. Work on the ''Keitum-Therme'' started in 2007 but stopped in 2008, after disagreement between the municipality Sylt-Ost and the builder, leaving the facility half-finished. Due to water and frost damage, the condition of the ruins has long deteriorated past the point at which work could be economically resumed. However, plans to demolish the structures have been blocked by lawsuits about the bankruptcy of the development company.<ref name=therme1>{{cite web|url=http://www.shz.de/lokales/sylter-rundschau/verhandlungen-ueber-thermenruine-gehen-in-naechste-runde-id8625221.html|title=Verhandlungen \u00fcber Thermenruine gehen in die n\u00e4chste Runde (German)|publisher=Sylter Rundschau|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Therme2>{{cite web|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/region/article108767301/Keitum-Therme-Sylt-wird-teuerste-Ruine-nicht-los.html|title=Keitum-Therme - Sylt wird die teuerste Ruine nicht los (German)|publisher=Hamburger Abendblatt|accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transport===\nKeitum has a railway station on the line between [[Westerland, Germany|Westerland]] and [[Nieb\u00fcll]]. However, long-distance trains and the ''Sylt Shuttle'' do not stop there. But hourly, there is a direct connection by train to Hamburg-Altona.\n\n==Notable people==\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Christian Peter Hansen|de}}, local historian (1803\u20131879)\n* [[Gustav Jenner]], composer and conductor (1865\u20131920)\n* [[Boy Lornsen]], sculptor and author of children's literature (1922\u20131995)\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Uwe Jens Lornsen|de}}, civil servant and symbolic figure for a unified Schleswig-Holstein (1793\u20131838)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n*[http://www.insel-sylt.de/orte/keitum.html Keitum tourist office]\n\n[[Category:Villages in Schleswig-Holstein]]\n[[Category:Sylt]]\n[[Category:Nordfriesland]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keitum"}
{"title_page": "Kehnert", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|type = Stadtteil\n|Town = [[Tangerh\u00fctte]]\n|plantext = Location of Kehnert in Stendal district\n|image_photo       =\n|image_coa            = Wappen Kehnert.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|52|20|24|N|11|51|11|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = Kehnert in SDL.png\n|state        = Sachsen-Anhalt\n|district         = Stendal\n|elevation              = 37\n|area            = 9.30\n|population         = 371\n|Stand             = 2008-12-31\n|postal_code               = 39517\n|area_code           = 039366\n|licence               = SDL\n}}\n\n'''Kehnert''' is a village and a former municipality in the [[Stendal (district)|district of Stendal]], in [[Saxony-Anhalt]], [[Germany]].\n\n==Town==\n\nSince 31 May 2010, it has been part of the town of [[Tangerh\u00fctte]].\n\n==See  also==\n*[[Tangerh\u00fctte]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Saxony-Anhalt]]\n\n\n{{Stendal-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|type = Stadtteil\n|Town = [[Tangerh\u00fctte]]\n|plantext = Location of Kehnert in Stendal district\n|image_photo       =\n|image_coa            = Wappen Kehnert.svg\n|coordinates       = {{coord|52|20|24|N|11|51|11|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan          = Kehnert in SDL.png\n|state        = Sachsen-Anhalt\n|district         = Stendal\n|elevation              = 37\n|area            = 9.30\n|population         = 371\n|Stand             = 2008-12-31\n|postal_code               = 39517\n|area_code           = 039366\n|licence               = SDL\n}}\n\n'''Kehnert''' is a village and a former municipality in the [[Stendal (district)|district of Stendal]], in [[Saxony-Anhalt]], [[Germany]].\n\n==Town==\n\nSince 31 May 2010, it has been part of the town of [[Tangerh\u00fctte]].\n\n==See  also==\n*[[Tangerh\u00fctte]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Saxony-Anhalt]]\n\n\n